SIMPLE: fate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fate
<hw>Fate</hw> <pr>(f⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>fatum</ets> a prophetic declaration, oracle, what is ordained by
the gods, destiny, fate, fr. <ets>fari</ets> to speak: cf. OF.
<ets>fat</ets>. See <er>Fame</er>, <er>Fable</er>, <er>Ban</er>, and cf.
1st <er>Fay</er>, <er>Fairy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fixed decree
by which the order of things is prescribed; the immutable law of the
universe; inevitable necessity; the force by which all existence is
determined and conditioned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Necessity and chance⟦br⟧
Approach not me; and what I will is <qex>fate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beyond and above the Olympian gods lay the silent, brooding,
everlasting <qex>fate</qex> of which victim and tyrant were alike the
instruments.</q> <rj><qau>Froude.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Appointed lot; allotted life; arranged or
predetermined event; destiny; especially, the final lot; doom; ruin;
death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great, th'important day, big with the <qex>fate</qex>⟦br⟧
Of Cato and of Rome.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our wills and <qex>fates</qex> do so contrary run⟦br⟧
That our devices still are overthrown.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whizzing arrow sings,⟦br⟧
<qex>And bears thy fate</qex>, Antinous, on its wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The element of chance in the affairs of life; the
unforeseen and unestimated conitions considered as a force shaping
events; fortune; esp., opposing circumstances against which it is
useless to struggle; <as>as, <ex>fate</ex> was, or the <ex>fates</ex>
were, against him</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A brave man struggling in the storms of <qex>fate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes an hour of <qex>Fate's</qex> serenest weather strikes
through our changeful sky its coming beams.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <ety>[L. <ets>Fata</ets>, pl. of
<ets>fatum</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Myth.)</fld> <def>The three goddesses,
Clotho, Lachesis, and Atropos, sometimes called the
<altname>Destinies</altname>, or <altname>Parc⟦ae⟧</altname>who were
supposed to determine the course of human life. They are represented,
one as holding the distaff, a second as spinning, and the third as
cutting off the thread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Among all nations it has been common to speak of
<xex>fate</xex> or destiny as a power superior to gods and men --
swaying all things irresistibly. This may be called the <xex>fate</xex>
of poets and mythologists. Philosophical <xex>fate</xex> is the sum of
the laws of the universe, the product of eternal intelligence and the
blind properties of matter. Theological <xex>fate</xex> represents Deity
as above the laws of nature, and ordaining all things according to his
will -- the expression of that will being the law.</note>
<rj><au>Krauth-Fleming.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Destiny; lot; doom; fortune; chance.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fated</ent>⟦br⟧
